Linux Basic Commands for DevOps

These are some of the most commonly used Linux commands during DevOps work. Every command below includes what it does and when we use it.

1. User and System Information Commands
whoami

Shows the currently logged-in user.

whoami

Example Output:

ec2-user
hostnamectl set-hostname aws

Changes the system hostname to aws.

hostnamectl set-hostname aws

After changing the hostname, logout and login again or run:

exec bash

To verify:

hostname
timedatectl

Displays current date, time, timezone, and NTP status.

timedatectl

Example Output:

Local time: Wed 2026-04-15 10:30:00 IST
Time zone: Asia/Kolkata
timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata

Changes the system timezone to Indian Standard Time.

sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Kolkata

To verify:

timedatectl
2. Hardware Information Commands
cat /proc/cpuinfo

Displays detailed CPU information.

cat /proc/cpuinfo

Useful to know:

Processor model
Number of cores
CPU speed
lscpu

Displays CPU architecture and summary information in a cleaner format.

lscpu
cat /proc/meminfo

Displays detailed RAM and memory information.

cat /proc/meminfo
free

Displays available and used memory.

free
free -m

Displays memory information in MB.

free -m
fdisk -l

Displays all disk partitions available in the system.

sudo fdisk -l
df -h

Displays disk usage in human-readable format.

df -h

Example:

Filesystem      Size  Used Avail Use% Mounted on
/dev/xvda1       20G   10G    9G  53% /
3. File Commands
touch file1

Creates an empty file named file1.

touch file1
ls

Lists files and folders in the current directory.

ls
ll

Displays files in long listing format.

ll

If ll does not work in your system, use:

ls -l
touch a b c

Creates multiple files at the same time.

touch a b c
touch file{1..7}

Creates files from file1 to file7.

touch file{1..7}

Files created:

file1 file2 file3 file4 file5 file6 file7
rm file1

Deletes the file file1.

rm file1

If the file is write-protected, Linux asks for confirmation before deleting.

rm file1 file2 file3

Deletes multiple files.

rm file1 file2 file3
rm -f file{1..5}

Force deletes files from file1 to file5 without asking for confirmation.

rm -f file{1..5}

Note: The original command rm -f {1..5} is incorrect because filenames are missing.

rm -f *

Deletes all files in the current directory without confirmation.

rm -f *

Be very careful while using this command.

rm -f a*

Deletes all files whose names start with a.

rm -f a*

Example:

abc.txt
apple.txt
aws.log

All of the above files will be deleted.

4. Folder Commands
mkdir aws

Creates a folder named aws.

mkdir aws
mkdir folder1 folder2

Creates multiple folders.

mkdir folder1 folder2
mkdir devops{1..5}

Creates multiple folders using brace expansion.

mkdir devops{1..5}

Folders created:

devops1 devops2 devops3 devops4 devops5
rmdir aws

Deletes an empty folder.

rmdir aws

rmdir works only if the folder is empty.

rmdir folder1 folder2

Deletes multiple empty folders.

rmdir folder1 folder2
rmdir devops{1..5}

Deletes multiple empty folders.

rmdir devops{1..5}
rmdir *

Deletes all empty folders in the current directory.

rmdir *
rm -rf *

Deletes all files and folders recursively without confirmation.

rm -rf *

⚠️ Dangerous command. Never run this command in important directories.

5. Navigation Commands
pwd

Shows the present working directory.

pwd
cd foldername

Moves into a folder.

cd folder1
cd -

Moves back to the previous directory.

cd -
cd ..

Moves one level up.

cd ..
cd ../..

Moves two levels up.

cd ../..
cd ../../..

Moves three levels up.

cd ../../..
6. Nested Folder and File Creation
mkdir -p folder1/folder2

Creates parent and child folders together.

mkdir -p folder1/folder2

The original command mkdir folder1/folder2 may fail if folder1 does not exist. Using -p is the correct approach.

ls folder1

Displays the contents inside folder1.

ls folder1
touch folder1/aws

Creates a file named aws inside folder1.

touch folder1/aws

The original command had a typo: filder1/aws

mkdir -p f1/f2/f3

Creates multiple nested folders in a single command.

mkdir -p f1/f2/f3
7. Advanced Listing Commands
ll -t

Displays files sorted by latest modified time.

ll -t
ll -r

Displays files in reverse order.

ll -r
ll -a

Displays all files including hidden files.

ll -a
touch .aws

Creates a hidden file named .aws.

touch .aws

The original command had a typo: tpuch .aws

ll -ltr

Displays files in long listing format, sorted by oldest modified time.

ll -ltr
ll -rtl

Displays files in reverse order with long listing.

ll -rtl
ll --color=auto

Displays files with colored output.

ll --color=auto

The original command ll -l=ll is incorrect.

8. File Content Commands
cat aws

Displays the content of the file aws.

cat aws
cat > aws

Creates a file and allows you to enter content.

cat > aws

Example:

cat > aws
Hello DevOps
Welcome to Linux

After typing the content, press:

Ctrl + D

to save and exit.

cat >> aws

Appends new content to an existing file.

cat >> aws

Example:

cat >> aws
This line will be added to the existing file.

Then press:

Ctrl + D
9. Copy and Move Commands
cp source destination

Copies a file from one location to another.

cp source destination

Example:

cp file1 backup.txt

This copies file1 into a new file called backup.txt.

To copy a file into a folder:

cp file1 folder1/
cp -r source_folder destination_folder

Copies a folder and all its contents.

cp -r folder1 folder2

-r means recursive.

mv source destination

Moves or renames a file or folder.

mv source destination

Example 1: Rename a file

mv file1 file2

This renames file1 to file2.

Example 2: Move a file into a folder

mv file1 folder1/
mv file1 file2 folder/

Moves multiple files into a folder.

mv file1 file2 folder1/

The original command mv file1,file2 folder/ is incorrect because Linux commands use spaces, not commas.

10. File Reading Commands
cat file1 file2

Displays the contents of multiple files together.

cat file1 file2

The content of file1 will be shown first, followed by file2.

cat -n filename

Displays file content with line numbers.

cat -n filename

Example:

cat -n aws
tac filename

Displays the file content in reverse line order.

tac filename

If a file contains:

Line1
Line2
Line3

Output:

Line3
Line2
Line1
rev filename

Displays each line of the file in reverse.

rev filename

Example:

Hello
World

Output:

olleH
dlroW
head filename

Displays the first 10 lines of a file.

head filename

Example:

head aws

To display only the first 5 lines:

head -5 aws
tail filename

Displays the last 10 lines of a file.

tail filename

Example:

tail aws

To display only the last 5 lines:

tail -5 aws
sed -n '17p' filename

Displays only the 17th line of a file.

sed -n '17p' filename

Example:

sed -n '17p' aws

-n means do not print all lines.
17p means print only line number 17.

11. Word Count Commands
wc filename

Displays line count, word count, and character count.

wc filename

Example Output:

10 25 150 aws

This means:

10 lines
25 words
150 characters
wc -l filename

Displays only the number of lines.

wc -l filename
wc -w filename

Displays only the number of words.

wc -w filename
wc -c filename

Displays only the number of characters or bytes.

wc -c filename
12. Useful Keyboard Shortcuts in Linux Terminal
Ctrl + U

Deletes everything from the cursor position to the beginning of the line.

Ctrl + A

Moves the cursor to the beginning of the line.

Ctrl + E

Moves the cursor to the end of the line.


Important Notes
rm -rf * is a dangerous command. Always check the current directory using pwd before using it.
rmdir works only for empty folders.
Hidden files start with . (dot).
ll is usually an alias for ls -l.
Use sudo when permission is required.
Always verify before deleting important files or folders.
